<h2 id="_Toc113548516">Introduction</h2>


<p>The compilation of the data in the Tanella Boni bibliography started in June 2022, under the guidance of Dr. Lorna Dawes, Dr. Kwame Dawes, and the project manager Rezina Habtemariam. Modeled after the Kamau Brathwaite Bibliography developed by Kelly Baker Josephs (York College, City University of New York) and Teanu Reid (Yale University), in conjunction with the Carribean Digital event at Barnard College, this bibliography has been developed through a collaborative effort, including an online researchathon organized by the African Poetry Book Fund on November 4th to crowdsource additional items for the expansion of the library. The collection is housed in Scalar, making its contents globally accessible to all users. Scalar’s open-source authoring feature allows members to continue adding new publications to the library, keeping it up-to-date as much as possible.</p>

<p>The earliest items recorded here are “L’objet, le Statut et la Place de la Th&eacute;ologie Chez Platon et Aristote (The object, status and place of theology in Plato and Aristotle)”, Boni’s 1979 dissertation and her 1987 dissertation “L’idee de Vie Chez Aristote (The Idea of ​​Life with Aristotle), from the Universit&eacute; Paris-Sorbonne, where she earned her Ph.D. in Philosophy. The most recent entries include an interview between Boni and French philosopher Vincent Cespedes in his 2022 interview series, “Night of ideas” (NuitDesId&eacute;es 2022) recorded in January 2022 as well as Boni’s latest poetry collection published by the University of Nebraska Press in November 2022, “There Where It’sSo Bright in Me.” </p>

<p>The bibliography is organized into five main categories: Primary Works, Secondary Sources, Tertiary Sources, Works in Honor of the writer, and Interviews. Most of these include subcategorized fields to distinguish the creative and critical aspects of the writer’s work, her works in translation, and the varied formats of secondary sources including media, dissertations, book reviews, general overviews, etc. Several databases were used in building this library, particularly World Cat and Google Scholar, for their extensive catalog of thousands of publications and scholarly literature in many countries as well as the wide-ranging disciplines and sources they cover. The items are presented in the MLA citation format and organized according to each category, with the subsections outlined after the other, until the next main category.</p>

<p>Of all the categories, Primary Works has the most expanded section, specifically Boni’s publication of Critical Prose in French (one of the subcategories under Primary Works), with over a hundred items recorded. Even though substantial effort has been made to expand this resource, some categories in the bibliography are less extensive than others. The categories with the least entries are Works edited by the writer, Works in her honor, Tertiary Sources, and Non-English Secondary Sources. These areas could use further research, especially by finding cataloged old newspapers and journals featuring the writer or her work. With Boni writing primarily in French, a huge part of organizing involved translating titles and other details found online into English to determine the right placement of each work. This, along with the auto-generated translation of the titles (which have not been officially verified), poses a challenge of inconsistencies in interpretation, a gap that opens possibilities for potential research and engagement with the topic. An important strength of this study is having Boni’s French titles and their respective English translations compiled in this bibliography for efficiency in navigating the platform and an optimized research experience. Another contribution, and what may also be the underlying significance of this web-based compendium, is housing all publications of the author on a single platform, affording access to a variety of data, supplemental materials for one’s study, authoritative sources, and research recommendations.</p>

