<h3 id="bio">Biography</h3>

<p>b. 1954, Abidjan, C&ocirc;te d’Ivoire</p>

<p>Tanella Suzanne Boni is a writer and philosopher who has published several poetry collections, novels, and essays. Her most recent collection is There where it’s so bright in me (University of Nebraska Press, 2022), translated by Todd Fredson. In her work, the writer explores issues of women and gender in Africa, feminism, human rights, as well ethics and politics. She was the Chair of the Association of C&ocirc;te d’Ivoire’swriters from 1991 to 1997. Boni is a Professor of Philosophy at the University of Cocody-Abidjan, C&ocirc;te d’Ivoire. She received her Ph.D. in Philosophy from the University of Paris. Her novel, Matins de couvre-feu (Mornings after curfew, 2015), won the Ahmadou Kourouma Prize and in 2009, she was the recipient of the Antonio Viccaro International Poetry Prize. Her other notable awards include prizes from the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization; the Geneva International Book and Press Fair; 2018 Prix Th&eacute;ophile Gautier from the French Academy.</p>

